The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt at the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of leaders from the world's developed economies, no one can say which among them will be with the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with UK Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could make himself the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The backlash against globalization has been going on for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend appeared to be convergence, and people seemed to be consuming the same products everywhere.
McDonald's has illustrated this type of globalization: breaking into the stores of this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But in recent times, the character of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is becoming increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are increasingly specific), companies relocate their production closer to markets where the merchandise will be sold.
This weakens international trade growth.
Such an "on-shore" anchorage is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded with Japanese cars. They then began to produce these cars at home.
Currently, most "Japanese" automobiles sold in the United States are manufactured in the United States. But the reversing of globalisation is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotics engineering and the development of processes like 3D printing.
Thus, current criticism of globalization has a tendency to focus less on commercial issues.
But this evolution does not only reflect the slowdown of trade growth.
Consumers in wealthy countries are much more at ease with foreign products, and in some cases, even reliant on them, since constantly updated electronics and affordable "fast fashion" have become predominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, the current opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
Disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on unclear courts protecting the interests of foreign companies and supposedly infringing on national sovereignty.
The global refugee crisis follows : in Europe, in particular, anxiety over this influx may be an early warning sign of a broader rejection of immigration from failed and impoverished states.
Why do people in advanced countries fear strangers so much ?
It's not as if they had never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries constantly travel to distant destinations and hundreds of millions of people worldwide head to developed countries each year.
The problem lies in our way of traveling.
Today, we have a greater tendency to experience things quickly and superficially rather than immersing ourselves in a culture.
However, as modern game theory teaches, a one-time interaction is very different from continued contact.
If participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper base of understanding or cooperation.
Continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The obvious result of a superficial approach to current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are not inclined to provide a good or even honest service to people who will probably never come back.
Restaurants serve mediocre food (or worse) without a smile, taxi drivers scam you, and hoteliers lie about their facilities.
In addition, this little game may experience interruptions.
In destinations where tourism has become a source of foreign income, it also becomes a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
A few attacks in places like Bali or Red Sea tourist resorts are enough to trigger a deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with local populations.
The emblem of modern tourism is a massive cruise liner, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (to visit a beautiful island in the Caribbean or an ancient port in the Mediterranean), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new Royal Caribbean ship Harmony of the Seas aims to replicate all the climates of the world.
In fact, this ship over 30 meters long than the Eiffel Tower contains a tropical garden and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Tourist bus or train companies do the same to ensure the safety of their clients, by only allowing them to disembark at a famous site for a limited time, in fact just long enough to take a few photos.
This style of travel imposes a constraint on the capacity of local infrastructure.
You often lack space to stroll along the canals of Venice or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors stay within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, meeting only scammers who offer them trinkets or overpriced taxi rides.
The indigenous people don't particularly appreciate groups of tourists who gather around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor does anyone maintain a relationship of trust.
One easily comes to feel a certain nostalgia for that era when tourism went hand-in-hand with long stays and long-term encounters with very different cultures.
It would be obviously impossible, given the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or even months in the old monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for instance, can provide a much more appealing experience than a hotel or, worse, a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
World leaders could participate in summits like the G-7, living and working for an extended period of time in a foreign country.
Little time after the entry into World War II of the United States, Winston Churchill made this famous gesture of leaving the camp to go live in the White House for 24 days, in order to consolidate the transatlantic alliance of Great Britain, by deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity may well be the biggest enemy of current globalist populists.
